{
    include "registries/llm_config.hocon",

    "metadata": {
        "description": "A Neuro-SAN implementation of the Tolstoy DAG-style reasoning system.",
        "tags": ["tolstoy", "dag", "reasoning", "maker"],
        "sample_queries": [
            "What is 46048 x 42098?",
            """
{
  "problem": "What is 46048 x 42098?",
  "max_iter": 24,
  "k_answer": 3,
  "use_scratchpad": true
}
"""
        ]
    },

    "tools": [
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_reasoner",
            "function": {
                "description": "Human-facing wrapper for the Tolstoy coded tool.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string", "description": "Problem to solve with Tolstoy."},
                        "max_iter": {"type": "int"},
                        "max_active_nodes": {"type": "int"},
                        "k_answer": {"type": "int"},
                        "k_validator": {"type": "int"},
                        "k_gc": {"type": "int"},
                        "max_proposal_retries": {"type": "int"},
                        "use_gc": {"type": "boolean"},
                        "use_reasons": {"type": "boolean"},
                        "show_nc_answers": {"type": "boolean"},
                        "use_scratchpad": {"type": "boolean"},
                        "cite_problem": {"type": "boolean"},
                        "answer_temperature": {"type": "float"},
                        "frames_path": {"type": "string"},
                        "result_path": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are the top-level wrapper for the Tolstoy DAG solver.

Always call the tolstoy_solver tool. Never solve the problem yourself.

Input handling:
- If the user gives a plain-language problem, treat the whole message as the problem.
- If the user gives structured JSON or named fields that match the tool parameters,
  pass those values through to tolstoy_solver unchanged.
- If the user omits a field, let the tool use its default.

Return exactly the text returned by tolstoy_solver, with no extra commentary.
""",
            "tools": ["tolstoy_solver"],
            "allow": {
                "to_upstream": {
                    "sly_data": ["tolstoy_result"]
                }
            }
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_solver",
            "function": {
                "description": "Runs the Tolstoy DAG engine and returns the final answer string.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string"},
                        "max_iter": {"type": "int", "default": 50},
                        "max_active_nodes": {"type": "int", "default": 10},
                        "k_answer": {"type": "int", "default": 3},
                        "k_validator": {"type": "int", "default": 3},
                        "k_gc": {"type": "int", "default": 3},
                        "max_proposal_retries": {"type": "int", "default": 5},
                        "use_gc": {"type": "boolean", "default": false},
                        "use_reasons": {"type": "boolean", "default": false},
                        "show_nc_answers": {"type": "boolean", "default": false},
                        "use_scratchpad": {"type": "boolean", "default": false},
                        "cite_problem": {"type": "boolean", "default": true},
                        "answer_temperature": {"type": "float", "default": 0.7},
                        "frames_path": {"type": "string"},
                        "result_path": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem"]
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.tolstoy.solver_tool.TolstoySolverTool",
            "args": {
                "tools": {
                    "proposer": "tolstoy_proposer",
                    "validator": "tolstoy_validator",
                    "answerer": "tolstoy_answerer",
                    "equivalence_judge": "tolstoy_equivalence_judge",
                    "gc": "tolstoy_gc",
                    "scratchpad": "tolstoy_scratchpad",
                    "consolidator": "tolstoy_consolidator"
                }
            },
            "allow": {
                "from_downstream": {
                    "messages": true
                }
            }
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_proposer",
            "function": {
                "description": "Proposes the next DAG question to ask.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string"},
                        "active_facts": {"type": "string"},
                        "scratchpad": {"type": "string"},
                        "feedback": {"type": "string"},
                        "use_reasons": {"type": "boolean"},
                        "cite_problem": {"type": "boolean"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem", "active_facts"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.0
            },
            "instructions": """
You are the proposer for a DAG-based reasoning system.

Your job is orchestration, not calculation. Never solve the root problem or
compute intermediate values yourself. Instead, propose one next question whose
answer can become a verified DAG fact.

Key rules:
- Answerers will see only the proposed question text. They do not see the
  original problem, parent facts, or scratchpad.
- Every question must therefore be self-contained: copy any needed facts
  directly into the question and attribute them to the original problem or to a
  numbered parent fact.
- Every factual claim in the question must have an explicit source.
- The requested answer format must be precise enough that two correct answerers
  should produce the same final string.
- Answerers serialize their result through a `FINAL ANSWER:` wrapper. Do not
  ask for bare outputs such as "digits only", "no extra text", or "answer with
  only the integer". Instead, describe the content that should appear after the
  wrapper.
- Prefer rich, specific answers over yes/no questions.
- You may cite only ANSWERED facts.
- If the current graph already contains an answered node that solves the root
  problem, stop and point to it instead of asking another question.

If feedback is present, fix that specific problem before proposing again.

Output exactly one of these formats:

FINAL ANSWER NODE: <node id>

or

PARENT FACTS: <comma-separated ids>
PROPOSED QUESTION: <self-contained question>
RETIRE: <comma-separated ids or NONE>
REASON: <one short sentence>
""",
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_validator",
            "function": {
                "description": "Checks whether a proposed DAG question is structurally valid.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string"},
                        "source_facts": {"type": "string"},
                        "question": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem", "source_facts", "question"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.6
            },
            "instructions": """
You validate a proposed DAG question.

You are given:
- the original problem
- the cited source facts
- the proposed question

Check three conditions:
1. SELF-CONTAINED: the question includes every fact needed to answer it.
2. CITED: every factual claim in the question is explicitly attributed, and any
   quoted or copied content matches the cited source.
3. UNAMBIGUOUS: the question asks for exactly one well-specified answer format.

Do not judge strategic usefulness. Only judge structural validity.

Output exactly:
ITEM 1: PASS or FAIL - <brief reason>
ITEM 2: PASS or FAIL - <brief reason>
ITEM 3: PASS or FAIL - <brief reason>
VERDICT: ACCEPT or REJECT
""",
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_answerer",
            "function": {
                "description": "Answers a self-contained Tolstoy sub-question.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": {"type": "string"},
                        "answer_temperature": {"type": "float"}
                    },
                    "required": ["question"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.7
            },
            "instructions": """
You answer self-contained sub-questions.

Use only the question text. Do not assume hidden context.

If the question contains inconsistent premises, a false quoted statement, or an
internal contradiction that prevents a trustworthy answer, output:
CONTRADICTION: <brief explanation>

Otherwise solve the question and finish with:
FINAL ANSWER: <answer body>

Important:
- Treat `FINAL ANSWER:` as a transport wrapper required by the system, not as a
  contradiction with the question's requested answer content.
- The `<answer body>` after the wrapper must follow the question's requested
  content/format exactly.
- If the requested answer naturally spans multiple lines, put the first line
  after `FINAL ANSWER:` and continue the remaining lines below it.
""",
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_equivalence_judge",
            "function": {
                "description": "Determines whether multiple candidate answers are equivalent.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": {"type": "string"},
                        "answers": {
                            "type": "array",
                            "items": {"type": "string"}
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["question", "answers"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.0
            },
            "instructions": """
You judge whether multiple candidate answers mean the same thing for the given
question and respect the same required answer format.

Output exactly:
VERDICT: SAME or DIFFERENT
CANONICAL: <best canonical answer if SAME>
""",
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_consolidator",
            "function": {
                "description": "Selects a set of facts that should be merged into a denser summary fact.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string"},
                        "active_facts": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem", "active_facts"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.0
            },
            "instructions": """
You help a DAG reasoner keep its active fact set compact.

Pick two or more answered facts whose content can be merged into one new,
self-contained fact that will be easier for later questions to cite.

The merge question must quote the needed fact content directly, remain
self-contained, and request a concrete output format.

Output exactly:
CONSOLIDATE: <comma-separated fact ids>
MERGE QUESTION: <self-contained merge question>
""",
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_gc",
            "function": {
                "description": "Suggests which active answered facts can be retired after a new fact is added.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string"},
                        "active_facts": {"type": "string"},
                        "new_fact": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem", "active_facts", "new_fact"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.2
            },
            "instructions": """
You are a conservative garbage collector for DAG facts.

Retire a fact only when the newly confirmed fact clearly absorbs it or makes it
irrelevant for future work. When unsure, keep the fact.

Output exactly:
RETIRE: <comma-separated ids or NONE>
REASON <id>: <brief explanation for each retired id>
""",
        },
        {
            "name": "tolstoy_scratchpad",
            "function": {
                "description": "Updates a short capability scratchpad after failures.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "problem": {"type": "string"},
                        "scratchpad": {"type": "string"},
                        "event_type": {"type": "string"},
                        "question": {"type": "string"},
                        "result": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["problem", "scratchpad", "event_type", "question", "result"]
                }
            },
            "llm_config": {
                "temperature": 0.0
            },
            "instructions": """
You maintain a short working scratchpad for the Tolstoy proposer.

Summarize what the latest failure teaches the system:
- recurring validator mistakes
- question sizes that led to no-consensus
- premises that turned out to be unsafe

Return only the revised scratchpad as concise bullet points.
""",
        }
    ]
}
